<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-12-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-12-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="265" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d265">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hart</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-12-18"><hi rend="italic">December 18,
                                    1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 441.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In compliance with, the suggestions
                            contained in your No. 678, of October 23 last, claims circulars have
                            been sent to the United States consulate-general at Panama for the
                            benefit of American citizens who have lost their property by military
                            expropriations.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay</hi>.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>